<HEADLINE>
Please explain the $20 DTV fee for an access card
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> &quot;Jdguay&quot; &lt;jeffnospamg...@verizon.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-31T21:51:00 </POSTDATE>
Hi,
I am a current DIRECTV subscriber.  The other day I got an older HD DIRECTV
receiver from my brother.  I wanted to use it in the basement on a small lcd
tv over my treadmill.  I ran the cable, hooked everything up, and called
DIRECTV to activate the receiver.  After the usual ridiculous hold time, I
was told I would need a new access card.  I explained that the unit had a
card but was told I needed to have a new one sent to me for $20!  I hung up
on the gentleman.

Why can't I use the existing card?  My brother is no longer a DIRECTV
customer, hasn't been for over a year.  How does DTV justify this given the
fact that if I had cable I could hookup as many TVs as I want for nothing?

Thanks,
Jeff
</POST>
